-- China key share index posts biggest drop in 5 years, banks plummet 
-- By Chen Yixin and Pete Sweeney
-- Tue Dec 09, 2014 02:19AM EST
-- None



SHANGHAI, Dec 9 (Reuters) - Shanghai shares posted their biggest one-day percentage fall in five years on Tuesday, dragged down by a sell-off in the financial and property sectors, reversing a two-week long rally.

The CSI300 index <.CSI300> of the largest listed companies in Shanghai and Shenzhen fell 4.5 percent, the biggest one-day fall since June 2013, to 3,106.91 points, while the Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> which tracks all the tickers trading on the Shanghai Stock Exchange 5.4 percent, the biggest one-day percentage fall since August 2009, to 2,856.27 points. The largest percentage gainer on the Shanghai exchange on Tuesday was Hainan Mining Co <601969.SS>, which rose 44.0 percent, while the largest percentage decliner was Boyuan Investmnt <600656.SS>, down 10.0 percent.  Among the most active stocks in Shanghai were Bank Of China <601988.SS>, down 9.29 percent to 3.32 yuan; China State Construction Engineering <601668.SS>, unchanged at 5.03 yuan and Agricultural Bank Of China <601288.SS>, down 8.93 percent to 3.06 yuan.